.\" GNU-style manual page for nina configuration
.TH NINA.CONF 5 "February 2026" "nina 1.0" "File Formats"

.SH NAME
nina.conf \- configuration file and markup specification for nina

.SH SYNOPSIS
.I ~/.nina/config

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B nina
configuration file defines runtime behavior, rendering options,
style definitions, feature toggles, and file locations used by the
.BR nina (1)
command.

The configuration file is a POSIX shell script and is executed
using the
.B source
mechanism. It must contain valid shell syntax.

Only trusted users should modify this file.

.SH FILE LOCATION
The configuration file is read from:

.RS
.I ~/.nina/config
.RE

If the file does not exist, default behavior is used.

.SH GENERAL STRUCTURE
The configuration file typically defines:

.IP \(bu 2
File system paths

.IP \(bu
Feature toggles

.IP \(bu
Rendering styles

.IP \(bu
Color definitions

.IP \(bu
Deletion and indexing behavior

.SH PATH CONFIGURATION
.TP
.B NINA_DIR
Directory containing article files.
Each article is stored as an individual Markdown file.

.TP
.B INDEX_FILE
Path to the tab-separated index file.

.TP
.B ALIAS_INDEX_FILE
Path to the tab-separated alias index file, mapping each alias to
the real title it resolves to. Derived data, rebuilt by
.BR "nina --index" .
Has no effect if
.B ENABLE_ALIASES
is false. Defaults to a file named
.I index-alias.tsv
alongside
.BR INDEX_FILE .

.TP
.B ARCHIVE_DIR
Directory articles are moved to when removed, if
.B REMOVE_MODE
results in archiving rather than permanent deletion. See
.BR nina (1)
for
.BR --remove .

.TP
.B MACROS_DIR
Directory containing macro files. See MARKUP LANGUAGE, Macros
below.

.TP
.B PLUGINS_DIR
Directory containing plugin files. See MARKUP LANGUAGE, Plugins
below.

.TP
.B EDITOR
Editor used when modifying articles.

.SH FEATURE TOGGLES
The following boolean or numeric values may be defined:

.TP
.B ENABLE_COLOR
Enable ANSI color rendering.

.TP
.B ENABLE_LINE_NUMBERS
Enable line numbering when rendering articles.

.TP
.B AUTO_REINDEX
Rebuild index automatically after create or delete operations.

.TP
.B ENABLE_CREATE_PROMPT
Prompt user to create an article if it does not exist.

.TP
.B SHOW_LINK_LIST
Show the list of an article's outbound links after viewing it.

.TP
.B REMOVE_MODE
Controls the behavior of
.BR "nina --remove" .
One of:
.BR archive ,
.BR delete ,
or
.BR choose
(prompt at runtime for each removal). This is a string value,
not a boolean.

.TP
.B ENABLE_ALIASES
Enable alias resolution. When on, the indexer builds a
secondary alias index from any
.B "- Alias:"
header lines in an article, letting that article be opened,
linked to, and tab-completed under the alternate name(s) as well
as its real title. A real title always takes precedence over an
alias with the same name; an alias claimed by more than one
article is dropped. Off by default. See
.BR nina (1)
for the
.B "- Alias:"
header field.

.TP
.B ENABLE_MACROS
Enable macro expansion when rendering articles. See MARKUP
LANGUAGE, Macros below.

.TP
.B ENABLE_PLUGINS
Enable plugin expansion when rendering articles. See MARKUP
LANGUAGE, Plugins below. Off by default.

.TP
.B PLUGIN_PERMIT_WEB
Allow plugins to reach the network. Has no effect if
.B ENABLE_PLUGINS
is false. Off by default; see SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS below
before enabling.

.TP
.B PLUGIN_TIMEOUT
Per-invocation time limit, in seconds, for a plugin that reaches
the network or the rest of the knowledge base. Numeric value,
not a boolean. Default: 5.

.TP
.B PLUGIN_NO_WEB_TIMEOUT
Per-invocation time limit, in seconds, for a plugin that does
neither - pure in-memory work on the article being rendered.
Accepts fractional values. Numeric value, not a boolean.
Default: 0.5.

.TP
.B PLUGIN_MAX_OUTPUT_BYTES
Maximum bytes of output read back from a single plugin
invocation; output beyond this is truncated, not treated as an
error. Numeric value, not a boolean. Default: 65536.

.TP
.B PLUGIN_MAX_MEMORY_KB
Virtual memory limit, in kilobytes, applied to a plugin's
subprocess. Numeric value, not a boolean. Default: 262144.

Boolean values may be expressed as:

.RS
.nf
true / false
1 / 0
.fi
.RE

.SH STYLE DEFINITIONS
Style variables define ANSI escape sequences used during rendering.

Examples:

.RS
.nf
RESET="\\033[0m"
H1_STYLE="\\033[1;4;15m"
HR_SYMBOL="┈"
HR_STYLE="\\033[38;5;60m"
TREE_CENTER_STYLE="\\033[1m"
TAG_GRAPH_HEADER_STYLE="\\033[1m"
.fi
.RE

ANSI escape sequences must be defined using escaped backslash notation
(e.g., \\033) rather than literal control characters.

.B TREE_CENTER_STYLE
is applied to the center article's title in
.BR "nina --tree" 's
output (see
.BR nina (1)).
It works the same as any other style variable here - set it to a
different ANSI sequence, or to an empty string for no styling at
all.

.B TAG_GRAPH_HEADER_STYLE
is applied to each group heading (a tag name, or an island number) in
.BR "nina --tag-graph" 's
.B --tree
output (see
.BR nina (1)).
Same rules as
.BR TREE_CENTER_STYLE .

.SH TERMINAL BEHAVIOR
.B nina
detects terminal characteristics at runtime:

.IP \(bu 2
Terminal width via COLUMNS or tput

.IP \(bu
Color depth via TERM and COLORTERM

Horizontal rules and line wrapping may adapt to terminal width.

Color depth may adjust style behavior automatically.

.SH ARTICLE FORMAT
Articles are stored as plain text Markdown files.

Each article begins with a structured header:

.RS
.nf
# Article Title
- Author: Name
- Date: YYYY-MM-DD
- Tags: tag1 tag2 tag3
.fi
.RE

Header fields are optional but recommended.

.SH MARKUP LANGUAGE

.B nina
implements a lightweight, line-oriented markup language.
Rendering is stateless and processed line-by-line.

.SS Headers
Headers are defined using leading hash characters:

.RS
.nf
# H1
## H2
### H3
#### H4
##### H5
###### H6
.fi
.RE

.SS Block Quotes
Block quotes begin with:

.RS
.nf
> quoted text
.fi
.RE

.SS Horizontal Rules
A horizontal rule is defined as:

.RS
.nf
---
.fi
.RE

.SS Lists
Bullet lists use one or more asterisks:

.RS
.nf
* Level 1
** Level 2
*** Level 3
.fi
.RE

Numbered lists use:

.RS
.nf
1. Item
2. Item
.fi
.RE

.SS TODO Items
TODO entries are defined as:

.RS
.nf
[] Incomplete item
[x] Completed item
.fi
.RE

Completed items may be rendered using strikeout formatting.

.SS Inline Formatting
The following inline markup is supported:

.TP
.B Bold
.nf
'''bold text'''
.fi

.TP
.B Italic
.nf
''italic text''
.fi

.TP
.B Underline
.nf
__underlined__
.fi

.TP
.B Strikeout
.nf
--struck--
.fi

.TP
.B Highlight
.nf
==highlighted==
.fi

.SS Code
Inline code is defined using single backticks:

.RS
.nf
`code`
.fi
.RE

Literal unparsed text is defined using double backticks:

.RS
.nf
``literal text``
.fi
.RE

Line-level code blocks begin with triple backticks:

.RS
.nf
``` code line
.fi
.RE

Multi-line code blocks are not state-tracked and are processed line-by-line.

.SS Links
Internal links use:

.RS
.nf
[[Article Name]]
.fi
.RE

External links use Markdown syntax:

.RS
.nf
[text](url)
.fi
.RE

.SS Macros
A macro is written as
.B {{name}}
or
.B "{{name argument argument}}"
and is replaced with computed text when an article is
rendered. Two macros ship with nina:

.TP
.B {{date}}
Insert current system date.

.TP
.B {{time}}
Insert current system time.

.TP
.B "{{| N%}}"
Insert a progress bar filled to
.IR N "%."
An optional second argument sets the bar's width in
characters (default 20):
.BR "{{| 30% 10}}" .

An unrecognized macro name is left exactly as written; nina
does not treat it as an error.

Macros are not built into nina's program files. Each one is a
separate file in
.B MACROS_DIR
(see PATH CONFIGURATION above). Run
.B "nina --macro"
to validate the files in that directory and install whichever
ones pass validation; see
.BR nina (1)
for what that command checks and how it reports problems, and
the
.I Macros
help article shipped with nina for the full authoring
contract.

Macro expansion can be disabled entirely with
.B ENABLE_MACROS
(see FEATURE TOGGLES above). Macros are validated only when
.B "nina --macro"
is run, not on every render.

.SS Plugins
A plugin is written as
.B <<name>>
or
.B "<<name argument argument>>"
and is replaced with computed text when an article is
rendered, the same as a macro. Unlike a macro, a plugin is not
limited to transforming the text it was given: it may read
other articles in the knowledge base, and - only if explicitly
permitted - reach the network. A plugin may never write to any
file; this is enforced at install time, not left as a
convention for authors to follow.

Three plugins ship with nina:

.TP
.B <<TOC>>
Insert a bulleted outline of the headers in the article being
rendered.

.TP
.B <<Backlinks>>
Insert a list of articles that link to the article being
rendered.

.TP
.B "<<show_alert TITLE>>"
Insert the body (header stripped) of another article by title.
Useful for shared boilerplate, such as a standard notice
repeated across several articles.

An unrecognized plugin name is left exactly as written; nina
does not treat it as an error. The same is true of a plugin
that fails, times out, or exceeds its memory limit while
running: the original
.B <<...>>
text is left untouched rather than silently replaced with
nothing.

Plugins are not built into nina's program files. Each one is a
separate AWK file in
.B PLUGINS_DIR
(see PATH CONFIGURATION above). Run
.B "nina --plugin"
to validate the files in that directory and install whichever
ones pass validation; see
.BR nina (1)
for what that command checks and how it reports problems, and
the
.I Plugins
help article shipped with nina for the full authoring contract,
including the functions available to a plugin for reading
articles or the network.

Plugin expansion can be disabled entirely with
.B ENABLE_PLUGINS
(see FEATURE TOGGLES above), and network access can be disabled
independently with
.B PLUGIN_PERMIT_WEB
even when plugins themselves are enabled. Plugins are validated
only when
.B "nina --plugin"
is run, not on every render. See SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS below
before installing a plugin written by someone else.

.SS Hidden Comments
Hidden comments are defined as:

.RS
.nf
/% hidden comment %/
.fi
.RE

Hidden comments are removed during rendering.

.SH SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
The configuration file is executed as shell code.
Improper modification may execute arbitrary commands.

Article content is not executed as shell code.

This statement comes with one deliberate exception: an article
may invoke an installed plugin via
.B <<name>>
syntax. The plugin's own code is what runs, not the article
text - an article cannot supply or alter code, only choose
which already-installed plugin to call and what arguments to
pass it. Plugin files are restricted at install time to a
read-only subset of AWK: a file containing
.BR system() ,
.BR getline ,
or a redirected
.B print
or
.B printf
is rejected outright and never executes, on the theory that an
AWK plugin's only paths to the filesystem or another process are
exactly these three constructs, so excluding all three closes
the question rather than relying on a best-effort scan to catch
clever uses of them.

Within those limits, a plugin may still read any article in the
knowledge base, and - only if
.B PLUGIN_PERMIT_WEB
is enabled - issue HTTP(S) requests. Installing a plugin written
by someone else should be treated with the same caution as
installing any other piece of software: review what it does
before adding it to
.BR PLUGINS_DIR .

Terminal escape sequences in article files are stripped during rendering
to prevent terminal control injection.

